    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nWhen document color highlighting is enabled (via `vim.lsp.document_color.enable()`), the foreground for some colors is white when it should be black.\n\nFor example, `#F77F7F` and `#00BFFF`:\n\n---\n\n<img width=\"515\" height=\"235\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/89e18e19-64c0-4cc5-afc0-91b4a48e3863\" />\n\n---\n\nAccording to <https://webaim.org/resources/contrastchecker/>, the contrast ratio for [`#F77F7F` is 2.53:1](https://webaim.org/resources/contrastchecker/?fcolor=FFFFFF&bcolor=F77F7F), and for [`#00BFFF` is  2.12](https://webaim.org/resources/contrastchecker/?fcolor=FFFFFF&bcolor=00BFFF). In both cases the contrast is very low.\n\n[pastel](https://github.com/sharkdp/pastel) shows that the contrast color should be black:\n\n```console\n$ pastel textcolor F77F7F 00BFFF | pastel format name\nblack\nblack\n```\n\n### Possible Cause\n\nI compared the implementation in Neovim and pastel.\n\nThe most notable difference that I saw is the threshold. In Neovim, it computes the luminance and then compares it to `0.5`:\n\nhttps://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/f2cc0a249d20462619801a194b67f6ab1d48476c/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/document_color.lua#L47-L49\n\nMeanwhile, pastel [uses `0.179`](https://github.com/sharkdp/pastel/blob/v0.12.0/src/lib.rs#L733-L740):\n\n```rust\nconst THRESHOLD: Scalar = 0.179;\n\nif self.luminance() > THRESHOLD {\n    Color::black()\n} else {\n    Color::white()\n}\n```\n\nI modified the `lua/vim/lsp/document_color.lua` code to use the same threshold:\n\n```diff\n--- share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/document_color.lua.orig\n+++ share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/document_color.lua\n@@ -45,7 +45,7 @@\n   -- Source: https://www.w3.org/TR/WCAG21/#dfn-relative-luminance\n   -- Using power 2.2 is a close approximation to full piecewise transform\n   local R, G, B = (r / 255) ^ 2.2, (g / 255) ^ 2.2, (b / 255) ^ 2.2\n-  local is_bright = (0.2126 * R + 0.7152 * G + 0.0722 * B) > 0.5\n+  local is_bright = (0.2126 * R + 0.7152 * G + 0.0722 * B) > 0.179\n   return is_bright and '#000000' or '#ffffff'\n end\n```\n\nThe contrast looks correct after the change:\n\n---\n\n<img width=\"1101\" height=\"494\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/871afde4-200d-4967-b07e-5a1943ee4ceb\" />\n\n---\n\nIt also matches what pastel computes for every color:\n\n```console\n$ pastel textcolor F77F7F 00BFFF AABFFF 0011FF 111111 AAAAAA 555555 | pastel format name\nblack\nblack\nblack\nwhite\nwhite\nblack\nwhite\n```\n\nHowever, the way that [pastel computes every color component](https://github.com/sharkdp/pastel/blob/v0.12.0/src/lib.rs#L693-L699) is slightly different to [what is done in Neovim](https://github.com/MariaSolOs/neovim/blob/f2cc0a249d20462619801a194b67f6ab1d48476c/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/document_color.lua#L47), so I don't expect that the fix above is enough for all colors.\n\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nOpen a CSS like this with the `cssls` language server enabled:\n\n```css\n.test {\n    --1: #F77F7F;\n    --2: #00BFFF;\n}\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nBetter contrast of the foreground color.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.13.0-dev-359+g72bc6c5801\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nN/A\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nLinux\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nAlacritty 0.17\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nalacritty\n\n### Installation\n\nNightly build in the repository",
